{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\nEvery gate row in epic pastoral-aquatic-viper adjudicates against ground truth that does not yet exist in frozen form. The report's §5 claims (16/505 post-claim edits, 3/8 review misses in one defect class) must be re-verified, not trusted, and the finding-level TP/FP labels needed by E2/E3/E6 and R1/R7 need a committed, versioned corpus. This story only *freezes* those corpora and the validity gate; it changes no gate/source code (nothing under `src/`).\n\n## What\nFreeze two ground-truth corpora under `docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/` with a versioned README, land the SOTA report as their committed provenance source, and commit the mining/adjudication/kappa scripts, in these steps:\n\n0. **Land the §5 provenance report.** This change commits `docs/research/task-decomposition-sota-2026.md`, recovered verbatim from commit `143d5074e` (authored by task d39b / englacial-communal-conure, which **closed without landing it to main**). The report is the published baseline the `--verify-s5` re-verification table compares against, so it must be locatable in-repo. (Done as the first commit of this change.)\n\n1. **Mine the outcome corpus** — one row per reviewed ticket (~527 reviewed tickets), written atomically (`.tmp` + `os.replace`) to `runs/outcome_corpus.jsonl`.\n   - **Data source (verified — no git-object walk needed):** the mining script scans the committed on-disk event files under `.tickets-tracker/<ticket_id>/`. Compaction renames folded events to `<name>.json.retired` and **those `.retired` files are committed on the tickets branch**, so scanning both `*-<TYPE>.json` and `*-<TYPE>.json.retired` yields the full event history reproducibly, without any `~/.claude/jobs/*` artifact and without raw git-object walking (`git rev-list --objects --all` + `git cat-file` remains an equivalent authoritative fallback, noted in the README). Plan-review and completion sidecars are read through their clean public reader APIs (`rebar.llm.plan_review.sidecar.all_review_results`, `rebar.llm.completion_sidecar`), which are reducer-ignored and compaction-preserved.\n   - **Pre-flight completeness probe (mandatory):** before writing, the script counts distinct reviewed tickets discovered on disk; if that count falls below a floor of **500** (expected ~527) it halts with an actionable error (`tickets history incomplete`) and writes nothing.\n   - **Outcome-corpus schema** (documented in the README): `{ticket_id, ticket_type, level, post_claim_edit_class, reopen_count (int), force_close (bool), completion_verifier_fail_count (int, retention-capped ≤10), review_round_count (int, retention-capped ≤50), had_persisted_review (bool)}`. `had_persisted_review` is load-bearing: Step 3 samples findings only from tickets where it is true.\n   - **Exact per-count derivation (grounded in the event model — there is NO REOPEN/FORCE_CLOSE event type; all transitions are `STATUS` events):**\n     - `reopen_count` = number of `STATUS` events with `data.current_status==\"closed\"` and `data.status==\"open\"` (`rebar reopen` == `transition closed open`).\n     - `force_close` = true iff any `COMMENT` event has `data.body` starting with `\"FORCE_CLOSE:\"` (force-close writes no STATUS flag; it leaves a `FORCE_CLOSE:` comment + a missing completion signature).\n     - `completion_verifier_fail_count` = number of `COMPLETION_VERDICT` events with `data.schema==\"completion_verifier_fail_v1\"` (retention-capped at 10/ticket — noted as a bound in the README).\n     - `review_round_count` = `len(sidecar.all_review_results(ticket_id))` (retention-capped at 50/ticket).\n     - `had_persisted_review` = `review_round_count > 0`.\n   - **`post_claim_edit_class` closed vocabulary** (the §5.2 taxonomy; exactly one per row): `none`, `cosmetic`, `premise-invalidated`, `scope-reduction`, `approach-change`, `plan-authored-post-claim`, `ac-strengthened`, `operator-attested-retag`. An edit is a DESCRIPTION-mutating event (`EDIT`/`CREATE`-superseding description change) on the ticket.\n   - **Post-claim window (reopen-safe):** an edit is *post-claim* iff its event timestamp falls in `[first STATUS→in_progress, first STATUS→closed]`. For reopened tickets, edits in any post-reopen window are **not** classified here (the §5 signal is the first claim→close cycle); `reopen_count` is recorded separately.\n   - **Overlapping-class precedence (first match wins):** `plan-authored-post-claim` (no `## Acceptance Criteria` block at first-claim, one appeared post-claim) → `premise-invalidated` → `approach-change` → `scope-reduction` → `ac-strengthened` → `operator-attested-retag` → `cosmetic` → `none`. Example: a ticket with a plan at claim that post-claim gained an `[operator-attested]` AC tag = `operator-attested-retag`; a ticket claimed with an empty description that gained its whole plan post-claim = `plan-authored-post-claim`.\n\n2. **Re-verify the §5 headline claims** against the frozen outcome corpus (report §5.2). `mine_outcome_corpus.py --verify-s5` prints the derived figures; the README re-verification table and the ticket comment record each derived figure **beside** the §5 published figure marked `AGREES` or `CORRECTED-TO <n>` per figure (never a vacuous \"agreement or corrected numbers\"). Figures: post-claim-edit rate (§5 **16/505 = 3.2%**), substantive share (§5 **15/16**), persisted-review subset (§5 **8**), the **3 MISSED** asserted-capability cases (§5 **dc58-af7b, db7b-c8fd, 5886-d028**), the **4 CAUGHT-BUT-IGNORED** (**c8cc-68b8, f5df-0069, 115b-ceea, 8c4f-b81c**), the **1 UNKNOWABLE** (**3006-e198**). All eight case tickets are confirmed present in the store (`rebar show` resolves each). **Disambiguation:** §5's `db7b` is story `db7b-c8fd` (\"REVIEW_RESULT reducer-ignored sidecar\") — it shares its short id with the sidecar it discusses; the corpus and table pin full 4-segment ids.\n\n3. **Build the finding-adjudication corpus** — committed script `harnesses/build_adjudication_corpus.py` samples plan-review findings from the persisted `REVIEW_RESULT` sidecar payloads (via `all_review_results`), restricted to tickets with `had_persisted_review=true`. Target **~300 surfaced + ~100 dropped** findings, stratified by criterion id and by bucket, written to `runs/adjudication_corpus.jsonl`. Floor for the AC: **≥280 surfaced and ≥90 dropped**; if the population is smaller, all available are taken and actual counts recorded.\n   - **Exact surfaced/dropped bucketing (verified — `decision` alone is INSUFFICIENT):** a finding's `decision` cannot classify it, because overflow-suppressed advisories carry `decision=\"advisory\"` (identical to surfaced advisories) and novelty-dropped findings also keep `decision=\"advisory\"`. Instead the sidecar payload stores `findings[]` in a fixed positional order whose segment lengths are exactly `coverage.counts = {blocking, advisory_surfaced, advisory_overflow, dropped, indeterminate}`: `findings = blocking ++ advisory_surfaced ++ overflow ++ indeterminate ++ dropped`. The script buckets by **position**: `SURFACED = findings[: blocking + advisory_surfaced]` (shown to the agent); `DROPPED = the overflow segment ++ the trailing dropped segment` (sidecar-only, suppressed). This is exact and independent of the `decision`/`drop_reason` ambiguity.\n   - **Adjudication-corpus schema** (documented in the README; it deliberately **diverges** from `code_review_adjudication.jsonl`'s `{block-worthy, not-block-worthy, ambiguous}` vocabulary — this corpus uses TP/FP): `{finding_id, ticket_id, criterion, criteria[], source ∈ {surfaced, dropped}, decision, drop_reason (nullable), tp_fp ∈ {TP, FP, ambiguous}, rater_a, rater_b (nullable), rationale, impact, validity, priority}`.\n   - **TP/FP definition (co-located in README):** for a `surfaced` finding, `TP` = the criterion genuinely applies (correct surface), `FP` = spurious; for a `dropped` finding, `TP` = correctly suppressed (no real defect), `FP` = a real defect the gate suppressed. `ambiguous` rows are excluded pairwise from kappa.\n\n4. **Double-label and compute inter-rater reliability.** Two **independent LLM raters** adjudicate:\n   - **Rater A (primary):** LLM adjudicator with rubric `harnesses/adjudicate_rubric_a.md`, labels the full sample `TP/FP/ambiguous` (populates `tp_fp`, `rater_a`).\n   - **Rater B (independent):** a second LLM adjudicator with an **independently-authored** rubric `harnesses/adjudicate_rubric_b.md` and a **different model id** from Rater A, re-labels a **stratified-by-criterion ≥50-finding subset BLIND** to Rater A (populates `rater_b`). Rubric B is worded independently so kappa measures genuine agreement, not shared-prompt echo.\n   - **Rubric contract (both files):** each states the TP/FP definitions verbatim, instructs criterion-aware judgment (the finding's `criteria` + ticket plan are provided as context), and fixes output as one JSON object per finding `{finding_id, tp_fp ∈ {TP,FP,ambiguous}, rationale}`.\n   - **Kappa:** committed `harnesses/kappa.py` computes **Cohen's kappa** on the binary `{TP, FP}` labels of the double-labeled subset (ambiguous excluded pairwise), prints the value; README records it with both rater/model identities.\n\n5. **Apply the validity gate.** kappa ≥ 0.7 → labels are usable ground truth. kappa < 0.7 → labels are declared **unusable**, `kappa.py` exits non-zero, README + ticket comment document the failed validity gate; no labels are shipped as ground truth for downstream stories.\n\n## Scope\n- `docs/research/task-decomposition-sota-2026.md` (landed from 143d5074e — §5 provenance baseline).\n- `docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/outcome_corpus.jsonl`, `runs/adjudication_corpus.jsonl` (new).\n- `docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/README.md` (new/extended): both schemas, the `post_claim_edit_class` + `tp_fp` vocabularies, the reopen-window + precedence rules, the positional-bucketing rule, the retention-cap notes, the §5 re-verification table, the recorded kappa + rater/model identities, provenance, and the **exact regeneration commands**.\n- `docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/harnesses/mine_outcome_corpus.py`, `build_adjudication_corpus.py`, `kappa.py`, `adjudicate_rubric_a.md`, `adjudicate_rubric_b.md` (new; committed **alongside** `corpus_sample.py`). They do **not** reuse corpus_sample.py's ephemeral `TMP` scratch paths — they write final artifacts under `runs/` and scan `.tickets-tracker/` on disk. `mine_outcome_corpus.py` exposes `--dry-run` (smoke) and `--verify-s5`.\n- NO gate/source changes (nothing under `src/`).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `docs/research/task-decomposition-sota-2026.md` is committed (the §5 provenance baseline) and its §5 published figures are the ones the re-verification table cites.\n- [ ] `runs/outcome_corpus.jsonl` is committed with one row per reviewed ticket carrying `post_claim_edit_class` (closed §5.2 vocabulary, assigned by the reopen-window + precedence rules) and the four counts derived by the exact event predicates above (`reopen_count` from STATUS closed→open, `force_close` from a `FORCE_CLOSE:` comment, `completion_verifier_fail_count` from `COMPLETION_VERDICT`/`completion_verifier_fail_v1`, `review_round_count` from `all_review_results`); `harnesses/mine_outcome_corpus.py` is committed, its `--dry-run` exits 0, and `runs/README.md` documents the schema, the retention caps, and the exact regeneration command that reproduces the corpus from the committed `.tickets-tracker` event files alone. Proving command: `python .../mine_outcome_corpus.py --dry-run` exits 0 and `wc -l runs/outcome_corpus.jsonl` ≥ 500.\n- [ ] `mine_outcome_corpus.py --verify-s5` re-derives the §5 figures and the README re-verification table records, **per figure**, the derived value beside the §5 published value marked `AGREES` or `CORRECTED-TO <n>`: post-claim-edit rate (§5 16/505), substantive share (§5 15/16), the 3-MISSED asserted-capability defect class on **dc58-af7b/db7b-c8fd/5886-d028**, the 4 CAUGHT-BUT-IGNORED, and the 1 UNKNOWABLE — no figure left as \"agreement OR corrected\".\n- [ ] `runs/adjudication_corpus.jsonl` is committed with **≥280 surfaced + ≥90 dropped** findings (target ~300 + ~100), bucketed by the positional `coverage.counts` split (NOT by `decision`), stratified by criterion, each carrying `source`, `criterion`, `tp_fp ∈ {TP, FP, ambiguous}`, and a `rationale`, following the README adjudication-schema table. Proving command: a python/jq check that every row has `source`, `tp_fp`, `rationale` and the surfaced/dropped counts meet the floor.\n- [ ] Inter-rater reliability on a **stratified-by-criterion ≥50-finding double-labeled subset** — Rater A (LLM, rubric A) vs Rater B (independent LLM, rubric B, different model, blind) — reaches **Cohen's kappa ≥ 0.7** on the binary `{TP, FP}` labels (ambiguous excluded pairwise), computed by committed `harnesses/kappa.py` and recorded in `runs/README.md` with both rater/model identities; if kappa < 0.7 the labels are declared unusable, `kappa.py` exits non-zero, and README + ticket document the failed validity gate. Proving command: `python .../kappa.py runs/adjudication_corpus.jsonl` prints kappa and the README value matches."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784160136556504001,"uuid":"a65f108c-73a1-407c-bb69-71416da1ec90"}